  "description": "\u003cp\u003e\u003cb\u003eThe \u003ci\u003eSunday Times\u003c/i\u003e Top Ten bestseller.\u003c/b\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cb\u003eWinner of the Orwell Prize 2018.\u003c/b\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cb\u003eNamed the most 'Rebellious Read of the 21st Century' in a Scottish Book Trust poll.\u003c/b\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cb\u003e\u003c/b\u003e\u003cbr\u003eDarren McGarvey has experienced poverty and its devastating effects first-hand. He knows why people from deprived communities all around Britain feel angry and unheard. And he wants to explain . . . \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eSo he invites you to come on a safari of sorts. But not the kind where the wildlife is surveyed from a safe distance. This book takes you inside the experience of poverty to show how the pressures really feel and how hard their legacy is to overcome. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eArguing that both the political left and right misunderstand poverty as it is actually lived, McGarvey sets out what everybody – including himself – could do to change things. Razor-sharp, fearless and brutally honest,\u003ci\u003e Poverty Safari\u003c/i\u003e is an unforgettable insight into modern Britain.\u003c/p\u003e",
